<font color="#FF0000">WAR  IS NOT FAIR, WHAT IS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Sep 21  0:54:31 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc,<br><br>
Rules of engagement made by politicians for their own reasons and not the rules created by the fighting machine.<br><br>
There was always little doubt that we could have finished the war.  Strikes on the northern dikes along would have stopped it, but starvation would have been the result due to the loss of the fields.<br><br>
During the Line Backer raids they ran out of ammunition.  The sky was clear and they were on their knees.  We were asked to stop while they recovered. FACT.<br><br>
Worked the trails really hard with the new specter gun ship.  Backed off too much interdiction.  This crap continually happened.  We fed the military machine which fed the industrial complex, which in turn caused jobs and money for those at home.  Not bad.  End it too soon and the economy ca not prosper.<br><br>
I used to fly over Haiphong harbor and see the allied ships from Canada and other nations along side the Russian ships offloading there cargo.  Got to keep them fighting.  Could not bomb the piers for fear of hitting allied shipping.  Many countries got rich off this conflict.  Whats a few lives for years of industrial growth.  Doc I fought in this war and believed in my country, but the political crap was too much.<br><br>
We could have stopped it many times, but could we have occupied the country.  Doubtful, not enough resolve.  Would it have saved lives on both sides, sure<br><br>
We divided the country in half and created safe zones for the enemy.  Politically incorrect to go all out.<br><br>
We promised not to do it in Iraq.  Started out the right way, but what did we do when the solution was at hand.  I can't tell you the real naswers, but we still haven't stopped political and economic conflict.  Look at history which we are doomed to repeat.<br><br>
SW<br><br>

